North Korea tested their first ICBM, the Hwasong-14, in July of 2017. This was then followed by a test of a more extreme ICBM, the Hwasong-15, in November of 2017 [https://missilethreat.csis.org/country/dprk/]. Though at the time it appeared that North Korea was quickly developing an ICBM with the intent of one day launching it, reports of this appeared to die down. However, after a second summit between Trump and Kim in May of 2019 in an attempt to brokerage peace fell through, it was reported by the Seoul intelligence service that cargo vehicle movement was spotted at the site in which is known for ICBM development [http://time.com/5546740/north-korea-icbm-uranium-sanumdong-vehicle-activity/]. It seems very likely that North Korea has chosen to restart their ICBM development and testing program after the summit fell through, however, under the assumption that the program was just restarted it seems unlikely that the ICBMs would have the capability to be launched successfully before 1 January 2020.

North Korea launched 23 missiles in 2017, one of which was the Hwasong-14 intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM) proving they were making strides in their missile program. However, the country's scientists and engineers have not proven that they are capable of developing an ICBM that can reenter the Earths atmosphere without burning. While the country has ceased to launch anymore missiles, expert warn that Mr. Kim has begun mass production of his weapons in the event that they are attacked. It is unlikely that North Korea will launch an ICBM before January 2020 because they have been unsuccessful in developing an missile that does not burn up on reentry, and they have shifted their focus from launches to mass production.

(I notice the question makes no mention of a nuclear or other warhead on the ICBM.) From the public information I have seen & heard, it seems likely to me that North Korea has used up enough of its nuclear weapon & missile resources in testing and/or lost enough of them in an accident to stop them, with little or no ability to replenish or repair. I believe this is what has brought them to the negotiating table. I also believe that US intelligence knows this, which is why they are not desperate to negotiate. There is much that is kept secret by North Korea and the US, including how quickly and how much of the requisite resources North Korea can slowly scrape together over time despite economic sanctions, and so I don't know the situation for sure, hence I have not set my probability to 0%.

North Korea benefits from the Trump Administration's negotiation tactics. Never before has a US president been so accommodating or attentive. ICBM and nuclear tests are intended to frighten, intimidate, and capture attention. Doing so before January 2020 might destabilize US support for Trump, thus jeopardizing North Korea's ability to negotiate on a world stage. This could ultimately mean significant issues within North Korea, where they are struggling for food and medicine that could be easily provided by a brokered partnership with South Korea and the west. Further, China is likely to want to improve North Korea's ability to trade with other global partners as a potential longer term method of avoiding the impact of future trade wars, so they are likely to push North Korea to act calmly rather than launching tests.
